events.description: Roman emperor Julian leaves Antioch with an army of 90,000 to attack the Sasanian Empire, in a campaign which would bring about his own death.

events.description: The Livonian Order is defeated in the Battle of Aizkraukle by the Grand Duchy of Lithuania.

events.description: King Henry VII of England issues letters patent to John Cabot and his sons, authorising them to explore unknown lands.
events.html: • 1496 – King Henry VII of England issues letters patent to John Cabot and his sons, authorising them to explore unknown lands.

events.html: • 1616 – Nicolaus Copernicus's book On the Revolutions of the Heavenly Spheres is added to the Index of Forbidden Books 73 years after it was first published.

events.description: Antonio de Ulloa, the first Spanish governor of Louisiana, arrives in New Orleans.
events.html: • 1766 – Antonio de Ulloa, the first Spanish governor of Louisiana, arrives in New Orleans.

events.description: Boston Massacre: Five Americans, including Crispus Attucks, are fatally shot by British troops in an event that would contribute to the outbreak of the American Revolutionary War (also known as the American War of Independence) five years later.
events.html: • 1770 – Boston Massacre: Five Americans, including Crispus Attucks, are fatally shot by British troops in an event that would contribute to the outbreak of the American Revolutionary War (also known as the American War of Independence) five years later.

events.description: Peninsular War: A French force under the command of Marshal Victor is routed while trying to prevent an Anglo-Spanish-Portuguese army from lifting the Siege of Cádiz in the Battle of Barrosa.
events.html: • 1811 – Peninsular War: A French force under the command of Marshal Victor is routed while trying to prevent an Anglo-Spanish-Portuguese army from lifting the Siege of Cádiz in the Battle of Barrosa.[2]

events.description: First Anglo-Burmese War: The British officially declare war on Burma.
events.html: • 1824 – First Anglo-Burmese War: The British officially declare war on Burma.

events.description: Roberto Cofresí, one of the last successful Caribbean pirates, is defeated in combat and captured by authorities.
events.html: • 1825 – Roberto Cofresí, one of the last successful Caribbean pirates, is defeated in combat and captured by authorities.[3]

events.description: Samuel Colt patents the first production-model revolver, the .34-caliber.
events.html: • 1836 – Samuel Colt patents the first production-model revolver, the .34-caliber.[4]

events.description: The Britannia Bridge across the Menai Strait between the island of Anglesey and the mainland of Wales is opened.
events.html: • 1850 – The Britannia Bridge across the Menai Strait between the island of Anglesey and the mainland of Wales is opened.[5]

events.description: Parma, Tuscany, Modena and Romagna vote in referendums to join the Kingdom of Sardinia.
events.html: • 1860 – Parma, Tuscany, Modena and Romagna vote in referendums to join the Kingdom of Sardinia.

events.description: Mefistofele, an opera by Arrigo Boito, receives its premiere performance at La Scala.
events.html: • 1868 – Mefistofele, an opera by Arrigo Boito, receives its premiere performance at La Scala.

events.description: George Westinghouse patents the air brake.
events.html: • 1872 – George Westinghouse patents the air brake.

events.description: Moro Rebellion: United States Army troops bring overwhelming force against the native Moros in the First Battle of Bud Dajo, leaving only six survivors.
events.html: • 1906 – Moro Rebellion: United States Army troops bring overwhelming force against the native Moros in the First Battle of Bud Dajo, leaving only six survivors.

events.description: Italo-Turkish War: Italian forces are the first to use airships for military purposes, employing them for reconnaissance behind Turkish lines.
events.html: • 1912 – Italo-Turkish War: Italian forces are the first to use airships for military purposes, employing them for reconnaissance behind Turkish lines.

events.description: The British Raj: Gandhi–Irwin Pact is signed.
events.html: • 1931 – The British Raj: Gandhi–Irwin Pact is signed.

events.description: Adolf Hitler's Nazi Party receives 43.9% at the Reichstag elections, which allows the Nazis to later pass the Enabling Act and establish a dictatorship.
events.html: • 1933 – Adolf Hitler's Nazi Party receives 43.9% at the Reichstag elections, which allows the Nazis to later pass the Enabling Act and establish a dictatorship.

events.description: Spanish Civil War: The National Defence Council seizes control of the republican government in a coup d'etat, with the intention of negotiating an end to the war.
events.html: • 1939 – Spanish Civil War: The National Defence Council seizes control of the republican government in a coup d'etat, with the intention of negotiating an end to the war.[6]

events.description: Six high-ranking members of the Soviet politburo, including Joseph Stalin, sign an order for the execution of 25,700 Polish intelligentsia, including 14,700 Polish POWs, in what will become known as the Katyn massacre.
events.html: • 1940 – Six high-ranking members of the Soviet politburo, including Joseph Stalin, sign an order for the execution of 25,700 Polish intelligentsia, including 14,700 Polish POWs, in what will become known as the Katyn massacre.

events.description: World War II: Japanese forces capture Batavia, capital of Dutch East Indies, which is left undefended after the withdrawal of the KNIL garrison and Australian Blackforce battalion to Buitenzorg and Bandung.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: Japanese forces capture Batavia, capital of Dutch East Indies, which is left undefended after the withdrawal of the KNIL garrison and Australian Blackforce battalion to Buitenzorg and Bandung.

events.description: World War II: General strike and protest march in Athens against rumours of forced  mobilization of Greek workers for work in Germany,  resulting in clashes with the Axis occupation forces and collaborationist police. The decree is withdrawn on the next day.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: General strike and protest march in Athens against rumours of forced mobilization of Greek workers for work in Germany, resulting in clashes with the Axis occupation forces and collaborationist police. The decree is withdrawn on the next day.[7][8]

events.html: • 1944 – World War II: The Red Army begins the Uman–Botoșani offensive in the western Ukrainian SSR.

events.description: Cold War: Winston Churchill coins the phrase "Iron Curtain" in his speech at Westminster College, Missouri.
events.html: • 1946 – Cold War: Winston Churchill coins the phrase "Iron Curtain" in his speech at Westminster College, Missouri.

events.description: Joseph Stalin, the longest serving leader of the Soviet Union, dies at his Volynskoe dacha in Moscow after suffering a cerebral hemorrhage four days earlier.

events.html: • 1965 – March Intifada: A Leftist uprising erupts in Bahrain against the British colonial presence.
